Temperature Converter Web App

Overview

This project is a mobile‑friendly Temperature Converter built using HTML5, CSS3, JavaScript, and jQuery Mobile. The app allows users to enter a temperature value and convert it between Fahrenheit and Celsius. It includes input validation, responsive design, and dynamic DOM updates.

Approach
I followed the assignment requirements by creating:

A text input field for temperature entry

Radio buttons for selecting the conversion direction

A Convert button that triggers JavaScript logic

A result display area that updates in real time

I used jQuery Mobile’s data-role structure to ensure the layout works smoothly on mobile devices.
JavaScript handles validation, conversion formulas, and DOM updates.

My Personal Spin
Although the assignment only required basic functionality, I customized the project to reflect my own style.
I added:

A full dark‑mode theme

Neon purple accents

Improved readability by overriding jQuery Mobile’s default white text

A more modern, polished UI that matches my personal aesthetic

This made the project feel more like my work instead of a generic template, and helped me understand how to take a simple assignment and elevate it with design choices.

Challenges
Overriding jQuery Mobile’s built‑in styles so the dark theme displayed correctly

Ensuring all text remained readable on a black background

Keeping the layout responsive while customizing the appearance

What I Learned
How to structure a jQuery Mobile page using data-role attributes

How to validate user input and update the DOM dynamically

How to override framework styles and apply a custom theme

How HTML, CSS, and JavaScript work together in a real project

How to take a basic assignment and personalize it in a way that still meets requirements